'''Ashburton Downs Station''' often referred to as '''Ashburton Downs''' is a pastoral lease that once operated as a [[sheep station]] and presently operates as a [[cattle station]].

It is located about {{convert|68|km|mi|0}} west of [[Paraburdoo, Western Australia|Paraburdoo]] and  {{convert|109|km|mi|0}} south west of [[Tom Price, Western Australia|Tom Price]] in the [[Pilbara]] region of [[Western Australia]].

The property occupies an area of {{convert|3005|km2|sqmi|0}} with {{convert|75|km|mi|0}} stretch of the [[Ashburton River (Western Australia)|Ashburton River]] running south west through the property.<ref name=R1>{{cite web|url=http://archive.agric.wa.gov.au/objtwr/imported_assets/content/lwe/rpm/catman/62%20part%202.pdf|title=Station Reports|year=1980|accessdate=5 April 2014|publisher=[[Department of Agriculture and Food (Western Australia)|Department of Agriculture]]}}</ref> The station once adjoined Peake Station on its western boundary.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article57969185 |title=Advertising.|newspaper=[[The Sunday Times (Western Australia)|Sunday Times]] |location=Perth |date=29 August 1920 |accessdate=30 April 2014 |page=9 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Other properties that it shares boundaries with include; [[Kooline]], Amelia, [[Wyloo]], [[Rocklea Station|Rocklea]], Mininer, Pingandy and [[Turee Creek Station]]s as well as areas of vacant [[crown land]].<ref name=R1/>

Established in the 1880s by a group of investors from [[Northam, Western Australia|Northam]] including [[George Throssell]]<ref name=R2>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hrF4C4RM_f4C&pg=PT69&lpg=PT69&dq=%22john+frederick+hancock%22+%2B+ashburton&source=bl&ots=bHbDI4D-iV&sig=13mpSHi5bXc1psQOzreK5uFtGWE&hl=en&sa=X&ei=odpgU_6EI42vkgWTpIDoAg&ved=0CEEQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=%22john%20frederick%20hancock%22%20%20%20ashburton&f=false|title=The Price of Valor|accessdate=30 April 2014|year=2012|publisher=Macmillan Publishers|author=John Hamilton|ISBN=1743347987}}</ref> by 1890 the property was struck by [[drought]] with the flock size being reduced from 16,000 in 1890 to 5,300 the following year.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article84561653 |title=Nor, â€“ West District |newspaper=[[Daily News (Perth, Western Australia)|The Daily News]] |location=Perth |date=5 August 1897 |accessdate=29 April 2014 |page=4 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>

In 1892 Throssell sold his interest in the property to John Frederick Hancock<ref name=R2/> and later the same year the property manager, Denis Bresnahan, retired from running the station.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article3030009 |title=Classified Advertising. |newspaper=[[The West Australian]] |location=Perth |date=8 January 1892 |accessdate=29 April 2014 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Ashburton Downs occupied an area of approximately {{convert|770000|acre|km2|0}}.<ref name=R2/>
The station was flooded in 1899 when {{convert|8|in|mm|0}} of rain fell in less than a month.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article33173939 |title=The Weather|newspaper=[[Western Mail (Western Australia)|Western Mail]] |location=Perth |date=10 March 1899 |accessdate=30 April 2014 |page=21 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> John Frederick Hancock died in 1902, aged 61.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article24841789 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[The West Australian]] |location=Perth |date=23 August 1902 |accessdate=30 April 2014 |page=6 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> The property was retained by Hancock's sons John, George and Richard, all of whom had been managing the station.<ref name=R2/> John Fredrick Jnr was the last of the Hancock brothers to own Ashburton Station, In 1911 the property had a flock of 30,000 sheep and produced 475 [[wool bale|bales]] of [[wool]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article74890467 |title=Stock and Shearing |newspaper=[[The Northern Times]] |location=Carnarvon, Western Australia |date=4 November 1911 |accessdate=30 April 2014 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>

In 1918 the property was passed from Hancock Brothers to the Ashburton Downs Station Ltd. At the time it occupied {{convert|755520|acre|km2|0}} and was stocked with 19,000 sheep and 320 horses.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article57998113 |title=Advertising. |newspaper=[[The Sunday Times (Western Australia)|Sunday Times]] |location=Perth |date=1 December 1918 |accessdate=30 April 2014 |page=11 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>

In 1949 the property was carrying a flock of 30,000 sheep but by 1951, following a severe drought, shearing had to be cancelled as the stock were too weak to be droved to the shearing shed.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article48200105 |title=Good Pastoral Rains Save Sheep From Starvation. |newspaper=[[The West Australian]] |location=Perth |date=7 June 1951 |accessdate=1 May 2014 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>

In 1979 the property was stocked with 300 cattle. In a good season the station is able to carry a herd of approximately 5,000 head of cattle.<ref name=R1/>

